definition.value: A dipeptide formed from L-valine and L-methionine residues.
A dipeptide formed from L-valine and L-phenylalanine residues.
A phosphatidylcholine 28:0 in which the two acyl substituents at positions 1 and 2 are specified as lauroyl and palmitoyl respectively.
A phosphatidylcholine 28:0 in which the two acyl substituents at positions 1 and 2 are specified as palmitoyl and lauroyl respectively.

An Ins-1-P-6-Man-1-6-Ins-1-P-Cer B/B'(2-) in which the acyl group and the ceramide base contain a total of 46 carbons and 0 double bonds, with either the acyl group hydroxylated at position 2 or the ceramide base hydroxylated at position 4.
A flavanone glycoside that is  eriodictyol substituted by a 2-O-(6-deoxy-alpha-L-mannopyranosyl)-beta-D-glucopyranosyl residue at position 7 via a glycosidic linkage.
A 1-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoserine(1-) that is the conjugate base of 1-palmitoyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoserine.
A dipeptide formed from L-valine and L-serine residues.
A tripeptide formed from L-valine, L-tyrosine and L-valine residues joined in sequence.
An Ins-1-P-6-Man-1-6-Ins-1-P-Cer(2-) in which the acyl group is hydroxylated at position 2 and the ceramide base is hydroxylated at position 4.

An Ins-1-P-6-Man-1-6-Ins-1-P-Cer C(2-) in which the acyl group and the ceramide base contain a total of 42 carbons and 0 double bonds, with the acyl group hydroxylated at position 2 and the ceramide base hydroxylated at position 4.

An Ins-1-P-6-Man-1-6-Ins-1-P-Cer C(2-) in which the acyl group and the ceramide base contain a total of 44 carbons and 0 double bonds, with the acyl group hydroxylated at position 2 and the ceramide base hydroxylated at position 4.
A phosphatidylcholine 34:0 in which the two acyl substituents at positions 1 and 2 are specified as stearoyl and palmitoyl respectively.

An Ins-1-P-6-Man-1-6-Ins-1-P-Cer C(2-) in which the acyl group and the ceramide base contain a total of 46 carbons and 0 double bonds, with the acyl group hydroxylated at position 2 and the ceramide base hydroxylated at position 4.
A 1-alkyl-2-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine zwitterion in which the alpha- and beta-positions of the 1-alkyl group are fully saturated.
A phosphatidylserine 34:1 that is the conjugate base of 1-palmitoyl-2-oleoyl-sn-glycero-3-phospho-L-serine, in which the carboxy and phosphate groups are anionic and the amino group is cationic.
An anthocyanin cation that is malvidin carrying two beta-D-glucosyl residues at positions 3 and 5.
A phosphatidylserine 34:2 that is the conjugate base of 1-palmitoyl-2-linoleoyl-sn-glycero-3-phospho-L-serine, in which the carboxy and phosphate groups are anionic and the amino group is cationic.

A phosphatidylserine 36:4 that is the conjugate base of 1-palmitoyl-2-arachidonoyl-sn-glycero-3-phospho-L-serine, in which the carboxy and phosphate groups are anionic and the amino group is cationic.
An anthocyanidin chloride that has peonidin as the cationic component.
A phosphatidylcholine 36:1 in which the phosphatidyl acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are stearoyl and oleoyl respectively.
An anthocyanidin chloride that has petunidin as the cationic component.
A 1-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the amino to the phosphate group of 1-stearoyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine.
An dichlorobenzene derivative that is used in the form of its trifenate salt for treatment of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease.
A phosphatidylethanolamine 36:1 zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the amino to the phosphate group of 1-stearoyl-2-oleoyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine.
An organic cation that is the conjugate acid of vilanterol, obtained by protonation of the secondary amino group.

A triphenylacetate salt obtained by combining vilanterol with one equivalent of  triphenylacetic acid. Used in combination with fluticasone furoate for treatment of bronchospasm associated with chronic obstructive pulmonary disease.
An oligonucleotide composed of three deoxythymidylic acid residues connected by 3'->5' phosphodiester linkages.
Any organic salt prepared using triphenylacetic acid as the acid component.
A mixture composed of vilanterol trifenate and fluticasone furoate (trade name Breo Ellipta) that is used for treatment of bronchospasm associated with chronic obstructive pulmonary disease.

A mixture of glycopeptide antibiotics originally isolated from the bacterium Streptomyces verticillus whose components all contain a thiazolinylthiazole moiety and can form complexes with redox-active metals such as Co, Cu, and Fe. (Bleomycins are very similar to phleomycins, but have a bithiazole moiety in place of the thiazolinylthiazole moiety).
An organofluorine compound and antineoplastic agent, used as its mesylate salt in treatment of metastatic melanoma.

A glycopeptide originally isolated from the bacterium Streptomyces verticillus which contains a (4'R)-4',5'-dihydro-2,4'-bi-1,3-thiazole-2',4-diyl moiety with a a 4-guanidylbutylaminocarbonyl group attached to the 4-position of the terminal thiazole ring. Like all phleomycins, phleomycin D1 can form complexes with redox-active metals such as Co, Cu, and Fe.
A serine/threonine kinase inhibitor that specifically inhibits human mutant serine/threonine kinase (B-Raf)
A methanesulfonate (mesylate) salt prepared from equimolar amounts of dabrafenib and methanesulfonic acid. Used for treatment of metastatic melanoma.
A cardenolide glycoside that is the 2'-acetyl derivative of neriifolin.

Colourless, endogenous or exogenous pigment precursors that may be transformed by biological mechanisms into coloured compounds. They are used in biochemical assays and in diagnosis as indicators, particularly in the form of enzyme substrates.
Phenol carrying amino and chloro substituents at positions 2 and 5 respectively. It is part of the degradation pathway of 4-chloronitrobenzene, CHEBI:34399.
An organophosphate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of 3-dehydro-D-glucose-6-phosphate.
An organic cation obtained by protonation of the two amino groups of 3,3'-neotrehalosadiamine.
A hydrazone obtained by formal condensation of the carbonyl group of 2-hydroxy-3-methoxybenzaldehyde with 2-hydrazinopyridine.

An indolyl carbohydrate that is the beta-D-galactoside of 3-hydroxy-1H-indole in which the indole moiety is substituted at positions 4 and 5 by chlorine and bromine, respectively. It is used to test for the presence of an enzyme, beta-galactosidase, which cleaved the glycosidic bond to give 5-bromo-4-chloro-3-hydroxy-1H-indole, which immediately dimerises to give an intensely blue product.
A semicarbazone obtained by formal condensation of the keto group of N-[(5-acetyl-3-thienyl)methyl]-2-chloroacetamide with the hydrazino group of semicarbazide.
An amino acid zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the amino to the carboxy group of 2-amino-5-chloro-cis,cis-muconic 6-semialdehyde
A carboxylic ester obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of phthalimidoacetic acid with the phenolic hydroxy group of 4-nitrophenol.

A carboxylic ester obtained by formal condensation of that carboxy group of {[3-(2,3-dihydro-1,4-benzodioxin-6-yl)-2-methyl-4-oxochromen-7-yl]oxy}acetic acid with the hydroxy group of 7-hydroxy-4-methylchromen-2-one.
A ring assembly that is the 2-(2,4-dibromophenyl) derivative of 4-[1-(benzylamino)ethylidene]-5-methyl-2,4-dihydropyrazol-3-one.
A 2,3-trans-enoyl CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of trans-2-icosenoic acid.
